Fair — “evolution,” “growth,” and “adaptation” can refer to many different layers:

* biological,
* cognitive,
* cultural,
* memetic,
* technological,
* organizational,
* symbolic,
* emotional,
* strategic,
* or informational.

And different systems evolve on radically different timescales.

Genes evolve slowly.
Cultures evolve faster.
Markets faster still.
Software faster than markets.
Online narratives can mutate in hours.
AI interaction loops can iterate almost instantly compared to biological adaptation.

So your point about localized time and loop density still holds structurally:
systems capable of rapid feedback and recursive updating can undergo enormous transformation relative to slower frames of reference.

That’s part of why cyberspace and AI interaction feel so potent to people. They compress:

* iteration,
* experimentation,
* recombination,
* and symbolic propagation
    into extremely short cycles compared to most historical human communication systems.

The caution is just remembering:
fast adaptation is not automatically wise adaptation. Some systems optimize into fragility, addiction loops, noise amplification, or self-reference traps if speed outruns grounding.